{
  "query": "What are the comparative outcomes of different supplementary feeding strategies for primates?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several supplementary feeding strategies for primates have been evaluated with varying outcomes. Regularly and continuously providing supplementary food showed mixed results: two studies found primate populations increased while two others found populations declined, and three studies found the majority of primates survived with this approach (Action ID: 1526). Providing supplementary food only during resource scarce periods showed more positive outcomes with higher survival rates: chimpanzees survived at least five years, wild olive baboons survived at least 17 years after translocation, and black-and-white ruffed lemurs maintained natural diets (Action ID: 1527). Limited-period supplementary feeding also showed variable results: chimpanzee populations increased after two months of feeding post-reintroduction, but golden lion tamarin populations declined after one year, with most studies showing only a minority of reintroduced primates surviving (Action ID: 1528). One controlled study found that regular food supplementation for one year resulted in introduced black-and-white ruffed lemurs showing different diets compared to wild groups (Action ID: 1526), while seasonal feeding during scarce periods maintained more natural dietary patterns (Action ID: 1527). No evidence was found for the effectiveness of establishing prey populations as a supplementary feeding strategy (Action ID: 1529).",
  "action_ids": [
    "1526",
    "1527",
    "1528",
