{"query": "What are the documented outcomes of translocating primates as a conflict management tool?", "summary": "Studies evaluating primate translocation as a conflict management tool have documented several outcomes. When translocating wild primates from development sites to natural habitat, research showed that the majority of orangutans survived in Malaysia, alongside other interventions. Three studies in Tanzania, French Guiana, and Madagascar found that a majority of primates survived for 5-30 months following translocation, though one French Guiana study found only a minority survived for at least 18 months. In India, rhesus monkeys remained at release sites following translocation from development sites.

For relocating 'problem' animals, studies showed positive outcomes: translocated 'problem' rhesus monkeys in India survived and remained at release sites for at least four years alongside other interventions. In Kenya, most crop-raiding olive baboons translocated from farmland survived for 16 years with similar survival rates to non-translocated populations. A study across Republic of Congo and Gabon found that 84% of 'problem' western lowland gorillas survived for at least four years after relocation.

Translocation from abundant populations to uninhabited areas showed promise, with one study in Belize finding that the majority of black howler monkeys survived for at least 10 months after translocation. However, no evidence was found for the effectiveness of translocation specifically to reduce primate predation by other primate species or non-primate species.", "action_ids": ["1558", "1559", "1522", "1534", "1422", "2465"]}

