{
  "query": "How does a permanent human presence at a site influence the success of primate conservation efforts?",
  "relevant_summary": "Permanent human presence at primate conservation sites shows mixed effects depending on the context and implementation. In mountain gorilla conservation, three studies found that numbers increased after tourist projects with permanent human presence were initiated, alongside other interventions (action 1512). This includes a site comparison study in Rwanda that found the number of immature mountain gorillas increased by 22% and snares declined by 30% after tourism projects began. However, not all outcomes were positive - one study in Kenya found that Tana River red colobus and crested mangabey numbers decreased despite tourism projects with human presence (action 1512), and an intensive tourism project in China for Tibetan macaques that included food provisioning actually increased stress levels with infant mortality reaching 100% in some years (action 1512). A tourism project in Madagascar had mixed results where two lemur species declined while one increased (action 1512). Habituation to human presence as a specific intervention also shows varied results - a golden lion tamarin population in Brazil declined after habituation (action 1519), while introduced lemur species in Madagascar showed good survival rates over 30 months after habituation (action 1519). The mountain gorilla population across Rwanda, Uganda, and Democratic Republic of Congo increased over 41 years following habituation to human presence (action 1519).",
  "action_ids": [
    "1512",
    "1519"
  ]
}

