{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the success of captive breeding and reintroduction programs based on the primates' rearing environment?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence shows mixed results for primate captive breeding and reintroduction success based on rearing environment. Primates born and reared in cages (ActionID: 1594) showed poor outcomes: most reintroduced golden lion tamarins did not survive over seven years or had higher mortality than wild-born tamarins, more squirrel monkeys died or were returned to captivity compared to wild-born monkeys, and black-and-white ruffed lemurs did not have overlapping diets with wild lemurs. Primates born and raised in free-ranging environments (ActionID: 1596) also showed limited success: only two out of three reintroduced black lion tamarins survived over four months, though reintroduced black-and-white ruffed lemurs showed diet overlap with wild lemurs. Primates with limited free-ranging experience (ActionID: 1595) demonstrated variable outcomes: while most black-and-white ruffed lemurs died over five years, most western lowland gorillas survived between nine months and four years, and their diets overlapped with wild lemurs. Large enclosure rearing studies (ActionID: 2507) showed that outdoor pen-reared black-footed ferrets had higher post-release survival rates than indoor-raised ferrets, though similar benefits were not consistently observed in other species.",
